# Figma Discovery First

- Before any Figma component-library write, complete one read-only preflight.
- Preflight owns discovery only. Use the modeling, composition, authoring, token, and QA rules for their specific policy details instead of restating them here.
- Inspect:
  - code source of truth
  - existing Figma pages and component pages
  - target component existence
  - QA/testing pages
  - variable collections and text styles when the component is tokenized
- Before the first write, emit one explicit preflight summary with:
  - `componentPurpose`
  - `usageIntent`
  - `realWorldUsageMatrix`
  - `representationPattern`
  - `stableShell`
  - `variantAxes`
  - `properties`
  - `regionClassification`
  - `atomicChildComponents`
  - `localFragments`
  - `documentationPlan`
  - `qaPlan`
  - `ambiguitiesRequiringHumanDecision`
  - `writeBlockedUntil`
- `documentationPlan` must include:
  - chosen shell layout model
  - explicit confirmation that final structure will use frames and auto layout instead of groups
  - preview surface strategy for contrast-sensitive child sections
  - page-level placement map for top-level authoring artifacts
- `qaPlan` must include:
  - required live-instance checks
  - required modes
  - any fallback QA allowed only as secondary proof
- If ambiguity remains after discovery, stop and use `AskQuestion` before writing.
- Hard gate:
  - do not write when any required field is missing
  - do not write when any candidate region is unclassified
  - do not write when `writeBlockedUntil` is unresolved
  - do not reduce preflight to a visual recap; explain intended usage and realistic combinations
  - do not write if the planned final structure depends on Figma groups where frames and auto layout can be used instead
